From 2137511715217a749e77596ec1949745d0a0fe55 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Fri, 17 Jul 2026 02:47:41 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Step 2 of the workflow-configurability plan: the generic
 pipeline engine

New WorkflowStage model - an admin defines any number of stages, in
any order, each with its own name, optional department tie-in, and
its own required permission (checked dynamically at runtime, not a
static decorator, since the requirement isn't known until the stage
row is read - this is a deliberate, necessary deviation from how every
other endpoint in this app is gated). Unit gets a nullable
currentWorkflowStageId - untouched by the existing Engineering/
Planner/Manager/Assembly flow, which this doesn't modify at all.

Built and shipped as new, standalone infrastructure on purpose, not
bundled with migrating the real pipeline onto it - that's Step 3,
deliberately separate so a mistake in the new engine can't take down
what's currently working.

New Configuration -> Workflow Stages page: create/edit/reorder (drag)/
activate-deactivate/delete, all reusing Step 1's ImpactWarningModal
before a risky change. New unit-level actions: advance, move-back
(only if the stage explicitly allows it), and an admin override to
jump directly to any stage. Added a small test panel on the unit
detail page so these can actually be exercised end to end, not just
CRUD'd with no way to prove a real unit moves through them.

Found and fixed a real bug while checking this before calling it done:
advance()/moveBack() originally computed a unit's current position
using only ACTIVE stages - but Step 1's own impact-warning system
explicitly allows deactivating a stage while units still sit on it (with
confirmation). A unit parked on a since-deactivated stage would
therefore be invisible to its own position lookup (findIndex returns
-1, indistinguishable from "hasn't started yet"), silently resetting
it to stage one instead of correctly continuing forward. Fixed by
computing position from ALL stages, while still only routing INTO
active ones - traced through every edge case (fresh unit, no stages
configured, final stage, deleted stage, multiple consecutive inactive
stages in either direction) to confirm this is actually correct now,
not just no-longer-obviously-wrong.
